// X-macro list of every C runtime symbol the FlowWing JIT must be able to
// resolve at IR-link time.  Each entry is included into:
//
//   (1) an `extern "C"` block in JITRuntimeSymbols.cpp that forces a
//       reference so the linker keeps the symbol in FlowWing-jit.exe, and
//   (2) a loop that pushes "<name>" -> &<name> into
//       llvm::sys::DynamicLibrary::AddSymbol so ORC's default
//       DynamicLibrarySearchGenerator::GetForCurrentProcess can find it.
//
// Why maintain this by hand?  The runtime is a static library that gets
// /WHOLEARCHIVE'd into FlowWing-jit, so the functions are *present* in the
// .exe.  On Linux `-Wl,--export-dynamic` re-exports them into the dynamic
// symbol table; on macOS dlsym(RTLD_DEFAULT) finds them.  On Windows MSVC
// symbols from static libs are **not** put into the .exe's export
// directory, so GetProcAddress(hProcess, "fg_pf") returns NULL and the JIT
// fails with "Symbols not found: [ fg_pf, fg_cs, ... ]".  Registering them
// explicitly via AddSymbol sidesteps the export-table limitation.
//
// Format: FW_JIT_RUNTIME_SYMBOL(name)
//
// Keep entries grouped by source file so it's obvious where each symbol
// comes from when new ones are added.  Sources were cross-checked against
// `nm -g --defined-only` on each libflowwing_*.a / libbuilt_in_module.a /
// libdynamic.a so the list is complete for the core runtime.  NOTE:
// raylib_module is intentionally *not* listed — `bring raylib` in JIT mode
// on Windows is not supported in this iteration because raylib exposes
// 500+ symbols; use AOT for raylib on Windows.

#ifndef FW_JIT_RUNTIME_SYMBOL
#  error "Define FW_JIT_RUNTIME_SYMBOL(name) before including JITRuntimeSymbols.def"
#endif

